Obtaining Posstratification-Frame fir 2019 UK General Election

Census Data

  • Load and explore Census data.
  • Clean demographic variables for BES data matching later on
# AGE: renaming and filtering
# age_code: census$Age..B...14.categories..Code, age_label: census$Age..B...14.categories..Label
census <- census %>%
  rename(age_code = Age..B...14.categories..Code,
         age_label = Age..B...14.categories.) %>%
  filter(age_code >= 3 & age_code <= 14) %>%
  mutate(age_group = case_when(
    age_code %in% c(3, 4, 5, 6) ~ "Aged 20 to 39 years",
    age_code %in% c(7, 8, 9, 10) ~ "Aged 40 to 59 years",
    age_code %in% c(11) ~ "Aged 60 to 74 years",
    age_code %in% c(12, 13, 14) ~ "Aged 75 years and over"
  ))

# EDUCTION: renaming and recoding
census <- census %>%
  rename(education_code = Highest.level.of.qualification..8.categories..Code,
         education_label = Highest.level.of.qualification..8.categories.) %>%
  mutate(education_recode = case_when(
    education_code %in% c(0, 1) ~ 0,  # no qualifications/low qualifications
    education_code %in% c(2, 3) ~ 1,  # intermediate qualifications
    education_code %in% c(4, 5) ~ 2,  # advanced level/higher education
    TRUE ~ 3  # other/not categorized
  )) %>%
  mutate(education_recode = factor(education_recode,
                                   labels = c("No/Low Qualifications", 
                                              "Intermediate Qualifications", 
                                              "Advanced/Higher Education", 
                                              "Other/Not Categorized")))

# SEX: renaming
census <- census %>%
  rename(sex_code = Sex..2.categories..Code,  # female = 1, male = 0
         sex_label = Sex..2.categories.) %>%
  group_by(age_group, education_recode, sex_label, Westminster.Parliamentary.constituencies.Code) %>%
  summarise(total_observations = sum(Observation))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'age_group', 'education_recode',
## 'sex_label'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

# Census Data Descriptives

BES data

  • Using unweighted raw responses to BES questions
  • Cleaning and recoding variables to match census data
# get rid of weighting variables and recode party voted for
# leep only relevant columns
BES <- BES %>%
  select(-starts_with("w")) %>%
  mutate(party_voted_for = case_when(
    b02 == 1 ~ "Labour Party",
    b02 == 2 ~ "Conservative Party",
    b02 == 3 ~ "Liberal Democrats",
    b02 %in% c(-999, 0, -1, 11, 12, 13) ~ NA_character_,
    TRUE ~ "Other Party"
  )) %>%
  filter(!is.na(party_voted_for) & party_voted_for != "Not Applicable")

# recode age, education and sex to match census data
BES <- BES %>%
  mutate(age_group = as.numeric(cut(Age, breaks = c(19, 39, 59, 74, Inf), labels = FALSE, right = FALSE))-1) %>%
  filter(!is.na(age_group)) %>%
  mutate(age_group = case_when(
    age_group == 0 ~ "Aged 20 to 39 years",
    age_group == 1 ~ "Aged 40 to 59 years",
    age_group == 2 ~ "Aged 60 to 74 years",
    age_group == 3 ~ "Aged 75 years and over"
  ), education_recode = case_when(
    education %in% c(0, 19, 14, 12, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 18) ~ 0,
    education %in% c(10, 11, 13) ~ 1,
    education %in% c(7, 8, 9, 16, 17) ~ 2,
    TRUE ~ 3
  ), sex_label = case_when(
    y09 == 1 ~ "Male",
    y09 == 2 ~ "Female",
    TRUE ~ NA_character_
  )) %>%
  filter(!is.na(sex_label))

# turnout variable processing
BES <- BES %>%
  mutate(turned_out = case_when(
    b01 == 1 ~ 1,
    b01 == 2 ~ 0,
    TRUE ~ NA_real_
  )) %>%
  filter(!is.na(turned_out)) %>%
  mutate(constituency = as.factor(Constit_Name),
         party_voted_for = as.factor(party_voted_for))

# recoding variables as factors
BES <- BES %>%
  mutate(age_group = as.factor(age_group),
         education_recode = as.factor(education_recode),
         sex_label = as.factor(sex_label),
         turned_out = as.factor(turned_out),
         party_voted_for = as.factor(party_voted_for),
         constituency = as.factor(constituency),
         constituency_code = as.factor(Constit_Code)) %>%
  filter(a03 != -1 & a03 != -999 & j01 != -1 & j01 != -999)

# merge BES with cluster groups data
BES <- merge(BES, cluster_data, by.x = "constituency_code", by.y = "Constituency_Code", all.x = TRUE)

# prepare data for model fitting
cols_needed <- c("age_group", "education_recode", "sex_label", "Constit_Code", 
                "turned_out", "a03", "j01", "y26", "constituency", "Cluster_Group",
                "party_voted_for")

BES <- BES %>%
  select(all_of(cols_needed))

# prepare data for turnout model fitting
BES_voted <- BES[BES$turned_out == 1, ]

# # # Comparing an XGBoost model to logisitc regression for turnout prediction #### Used an 80/20 traint7test split on the BES data and the same variables for both models

# 80/20 Train-Test Split
set.seed(17) # for reproducibility
training_indices <- createDataPartition(BES$turned_out, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
training_indices <- as.vector(training_indices)
training_data <- BES[training_indices, ]
testing_data <- BES[-training_indices, ]

# only relevant columns for XGBoost
training_data_xgb <- training_data[cols_needed]
testing_data_xgb <- testing_data[cols_needed]

# make sure the colums are all factor variables: 
training_data_xgb <- training_data_xgb %>%
  mutate_if(is.character, as.factor)

# drop NA rows
training_data_xgb <- na.omit(training_data_xgb)
testing_data_xgb <- na.omit(testing_data_xgb)

#  factor variables as numeric codes
training_data_xgb <- training_data[cols_needed]
testing_data_xgb <- testing_data[cols_needed]

# Remove NA rows after encoding
training_data_xgb <- na.omit(training_data_xgb)
testing_data_xgb <- na.omit(testing_data_xgb)

#  matrices for XGBoost
dtrain <- xgb.DMatrix(data = data.matrix(training_data_xgb[, -which(names(training_data_xgb) == "turned_out")]), 
                      label = training_data_xgb$turned_out)
dtest <- xgb.DMatrix(data = data.matrix(testing_data_xgb[, -which(names(testing_data_xgb) == "turned_out")]), 
                     label = testing_data_xgb$turned_out)

# turnout model : logistic regressoin
turnout_model <- glmer(formula = turned_out ~ age_group + education_recode + 
                       sex_label + (1 | Cluster_Group), # add constituency group
                       family = binomial(link = "logit"), 
                       data = BES,
                       # dont print out iuteratinos
                       control = glmerControl( optCtrl = list(maxfun = 2e5)))


# XGBoost Model
params <- list(booster = "gbtree", objective = "binary:logistic", eta = 0.3, max_depth = 6)
xgb_model <- xgb.train(params = params, data = dtrain, nrounds = 100)

# predict and calculate accuracy
logistic_preds <- predict(turnout_model, newdata = testing_data, type = "response")
logistic_accuracy <- mean((logistic_preds > 0.5) == testing_data$turned_out)

# XGBoost predictions
xgb_preds <- predict(xgb_model, dtest)
str(logistic_preds)
##  Named num [1:702] 0.873 0.845 0.699 0.834 0.834 ...
##  - attr(*, "names")= chr [1:702] "17" "28" "29" "34" ...
str(xgb_preds)
##  num [1:702] 0.317 1 1 0.999 0.999 ...
xgb_preds <- as.vector(xgb_preds)
xgb_accuracy <- mean((xgb_preds > 0.5) == testing_data_xgb$turned_out)

# compare accuracies
accuracy_comparison <- data.frame(Model = c("Logistic Regression", "XGBoost"), 
                                  Accuracy = c(logistic_accuracy, xgb_accuracy))

print(accuracy_comparison)

# XGBoost predictions for turnout probabilities
# Remove the response variable 'turned_out'

BES_for_xgb <- BES_for_xgb[, -which(names(BES_for_xgb) == "turned_out")]
dmatrix_for_prediction <- xgb.DMatrix(data = data.matrix(BES_for_xgb))
xgb_probs <- predict(xgb_model, dmatrix_for_prediction)
BES$predicted_turnout <- xgb_probs

# vote predictions
predicted_probs <- predict(party_model, BES)

# preparing predicted probabilities

BES_aggregated <- BES_cleaned %>%

    avg_predicted_turnout_prob = mean(predicted_turnout, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_con = mean(Con, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_lab = mean(Lab, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_lib = mean(Lib, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_other = mean(Other, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

Merging Census and BES data

# aligning education_recode levels in BES_aggregated to match census
levels(BES_aggregated$education_recode) <- c("No/Low Qualifications", 
                                             "Intermediate Qualifications", 
                                             "Advanced/Higher Education", 
                                             "Other/Not Categorized")

#  sex_label asfactor with consistent levels (if necessary)
if(!is.null(levels(census$sex_label)) && !is.null(levels(BES_aggregated$sex_label))) {
  levels(BES_aggregated$sex_label) <- levels(census$sex_label)
}
View(BES_aggregated)
# re-merge after aligning levels
poststrat_data <- census %>%
  left_join(BES_aggregated, by = c("age_group", "education_recode", "sex_label"))

# estimating votes on post-stratification data
poststrat_data <- poststrat_data %>%
  mutate(
    est_votes_con = total_observations * avg_predicted_turnout_prob * avg_con,
    est_votes_lab = total_observations * avg_predicted_turnout_prob * avg_lab,
    est_votes_lib = total_observations * avg_predicted_turnout_prob * avg_lib,
    est_votes_other = total_observations * avg_predicted_turnout_prob * avg_other
  )

Poststratification

actual_results <- actual_results %>%
  filter(Country == 1 | Country == 3) %>%
  select(ONSConstID, Winner19, ConVote19, LabVote19, LDVote19, TotalVote19) %>%
  mutate(OtherVote19 = TotalVote19 - (ConVote19 + LabVote19 + LDVote19))

# aggregate estimated votes by constituency
constituency_estimates <- poststrat_data %>%
  group_by(Westminster.Parliamentary.constituencies.Code) %>%
  summarise(
    est_votes_con_total = sum(est_votes_con),
    est_votes_lab_total = sum(est_votes_lab),
    est_votes_lib_total = sum(est_votes_lib),
    est_votes_other_total = sum(est_votes_other)
  )

# join with actual results
comparison <- constituency_estimates %>%
  left_join(actual_results, by = c("Westminster.Parliamentary.constituencies.Code" = "ONSConstID")) 

# calculate scaling factors and apply them
comparison <- comparison %>%
  mutate(
    scale_factor_con = ConVote19 / est_votes_con_total,
    scale_factor_lab = LabVote19 / est_votes_lab_total,
    scale_factor_lib = LDVote19 / est_votes_lib_total,
    scale_factor_other = OtherVote19 / est_votes_other_total
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    scaled_est_votes_con = est_votes_con_total * scale_factor_con,
    scaled_est_votes_lab = est_votes_lab_total * scale_factor_lab,
    scaled_est_votes_lib = est_votes_lib_total * scale_factor_lib,
    scaled_est_votes_other = est_votes_other_total * scale_factor_other
  )

# apply scaling factors to poststrat data
final_poststrat_data <- poststrat_data %>%
  left_join(comparison %>% 
            select(Westminster.Parliamentary.constituencies.Code, 
                   scale_factor_con, 
                   scale_factor_lab, 
                   scale_factor_lib, 
                   scale_factor_other), 
            by = "Westminster.Parliamentary.constituencies.Code") %>%
  mutate(
    scaled_est_votes_con = est_votes_con * scale_factor_con,
    scaled_est_votes_lab = est_votes_lab * scale_factor_lab,
    scaled_est_votes_lib = est_votes_lib * scale_factor_lib,
    scaled_est_votes_other = est_votes_other * scale_factor_other
  )
# sort by constituency
final_poststrat_data <- final_poststrat_data[order(final_poststrat_data$Westminster.Parliamentary.constituencies.Code), ]

# save final poststratification frame to a csv file
write.csv(final_poststrat_data, file = "final_poststrat_data.csv")
